properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. An Arctic ridge of high pressure will settle over the central prairies tonight dropping temperatures to near minus 30 C by Tuesday morning. These temperatures in combination with westerly winds of 10 to 15 km/h will create wind chill values of minus 40 or lower. Wind chill values will moderate slightly on Tuesday however similar wind chill values are likely again Tuesday night into Wednesday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Description: Rain, heavy at times is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Total rainfall: 30 to 70 mm. Highest amounts expected near the Fundy coast. Locations: central and southern New Brunswick Time frame: this evening into Tuesday morning Remarks: Rain, heavy at times, will persist into the morning hours on Tuesday. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow Squalls Tuesday and Tuesday night. Snow squalls are forecast to develop off Lake Huron and Georgian Bay Tuesday morning and then continue through Tuesday night. The most intense bands are likely Tuesday afternoon and evening with conditions slowly improving through by Wednesday morning as winds shift to the southwest. Strong winds will accompany these bands at times resulting in periods of blowing snow. Local snowfall accumulations of 10 to 15 cm will be possible under the most intense bands by Wednesday morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Flash Freeze Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A vigorous cold front will make temperatures drop rapidly Tuesday. Temperatures will climb above the freezing mark tonight before dropping rapidly below the freezing mark beginning Tuesday morning over the westernmost regions and this afternoon for remaining regions. Roads, still wet in many areas, may suddenly become very icy and very slippery. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Flash freeze warnings are issued when a rapid drop in temperature is expected, that can cause water from rain or melted snow on streets and sidewalks to quickly freeze. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
